## 1. Framework Upgrade Playbook (MANDATORY for any major bump)

> Added by <TICKET-ID> after internal cycle migrations (Next 14→16, React 18→19, Tailwind 3→4) shipped visual regressions and console warnings invisible to existing CI gates. The playbook formalises the pre/during/post phases used by Vercel, Stripe, Linear, and Atlassian for their own framework upgrades.

### Phase 1 — Pre-upgrade (BEFORE the migration ticket starts)

1. **Capture full baseline** via the manual workflow:
   ```
   gh workflow run upgrade-baseline.yml \
     -f migration_ticket=SCRUM-XXX \
     -f target_packages=both
   ```
   This commits the current visual + a11y + console state under `tests/e2e/upgrade-baselines/<ticket>/` for the migration to validate against.

   **MANDATORY rule (added by <TICKET-ID>)**: the `source-ref` field — and the `baseline_ref` field of the canonical `visual-regression.yml` workflow — MUST be a `v-baseline-*` tag (per §13.4 Visual Baseline Tag Policy), NEVER a commit hash that already contains an in-flight upgrade. The 2026-05-08–10 incident demonstrated this concretely: capturing baseline from (historical commit, pre-rename) (already containing TypeScript 6) produced a contaminated reference that could not detect downstream Tailwind 4 regressions. The rescue (<TICKET-ID>/385/386) re-established the baseline from the <TICKET-ID> tag `v-baseline-2026-05-06-auth-green`. Any reviewer who sees a `source-ref` or `baseline_ref` pointing at a non-tag must block.
2. **Read the upstream changelog**. Document expected breaking changes — specifically:
   - Class/utility renames (Tailwind: e.g. `outline` semantics changed in v4)
   - Async API additions (Next: `headers()` / `cookies()` / `params` async)
   - Framework default changes (Webpack→Turbopack, React 18→19 hooks)
   - Removed APIs (e.g. `next lint`, `forwardRef` deprecated)
3. **Define rollback criteria** in the migration plan: which check failures (CI gate? customer-visible bug? perf regression?) trigger automatic revert.
4. **Verify gates are operational**: VRT + a11y + console gate + Security Pipeline 9/9 on main BEFORE branching the migration. If any gate is red, fix it first — never bury a migration in pre-existing failures.

### Phase 2 — During the upgrade (per PR)

Each major version bump is its OWN PR. Combined bumps are an anti-pattern (no rollback granularity). Required gates per PR:

| Gate | Check | Tool | What it catches |
|---|---|---|---|
| **CI Layer 1-5 (Security Pipeline)** | secrets, deps, SAST, tests, build | existing | regressions in non-visual code |
| **CI Layer 6 — Visual Regression** | pixel-diff vs baseline ≤0.2% | Playwright `toHaveScreenshot` | Tailwind utility renames, theme token shifts |
| **CI Layer 7 — Console Errors** | 0 unallowlisted browser warnings/errors | Playwright `page.on('console')` fixture | recharts `-1` dims, Image aspect, hydration mismatches |
| **CI Layer 8 — A11y** | 0 critical/serious WCAG 2.1 AA violations | `@axe-core/playwright` | aria-label drops, contrast regressions |
| **CI Layer 9 — Performance** (optional) | LCP/CLS/TBT ≤10% regression | Lighthouse CI | bundle bloat from new dep tree |

If any gate fails, the PR is blocked. To accept an intentional change (e.g. "Tailwind 4 default border-radius is acceptable"): refresh that gate's baseline via the appropriate workflow_dispatch, document the intentional change in the PR body, then re-run.

### Phase 3 — Post-upgrade (after merge)

1. **Staging soak**: 24h on staging (or production preview channel) before promoting a feature flag or default-on. Monitor:
   - Browser console error rate (Sentry / similar)
   - Core Web Vitals (real-user)
   - Error Boundary triggers
2. **Rollback signal**: if any of the above crosses the criteria from Phase 1.3, revert the migration commit with a clear `Revert SCRUM-XXX (rollback per Phase 1.3 criterion: <which>)`.
3. **Audit run** within 7 days post-merge: `gh workflow run audit.yml` (or invoke `/audit <module> full` locally) to confirm no audit findings drift.

### Tooling locations

| Tool | Where |
|---|---|
| Visual baselines | `tests/e2e/visual.spec.ts-snapshots/*.png` (committed) |
| A11y spec | `tests/e2e/a11y.spec.ts` |
| Console-error fixture | `tests/e2e/fixtures/no-console-errors.ts` |
| Pre-upgrade baseline workflow | `.github/workflows/upgrade-baseline.yml` (<TICKET-ID>) |
| VRT/a11y per-PR workflow | `.github/workflows/visual-regression.yml` |
| Auth bypass | `NEXT_PUBLIC_VRT_BYPASS_AUTH=1` env var, honored by `AuthContext` |

### Rationale (why this exists)

internal cycle's 8-ticket migration backlog (<TICKET-ID>, 371-377) closed unit-test, lint, build, and audit gates with 0 failures — yet shipped 5 visible regressions detected only at runtime smoke-test time. The existing gates measure SOURCE correctness; this playbook measures USER-FACING correctness. Both are required to safely upgrade frameworks at the cadence demanded by `§12 Major Bump SLA`.

### 13.4 Visual Baseline Tag Policy (MANDATORY)

> Added by <TICKET-ID> after the 2026-05-08–10 incident, when 5 framework majors (TS 5→6, ESLint 9→10, Tailwind 3→4, lucide 0→1, react-hooks v6) and 9 Dependabot bumps merged into `main` in 3 days alongside audit FAIL fixes. Visual regressions (cursor:pointer, recharts theming) shipped because the in-flight VRT (<TICKET-ID>) baseline had been captured AFTER TypeScript 6 was already on `main` — the baseline was contaminated and could not detect Tailwind 4's downstream effects.

#### 13.4.1 When to create a baseline tag

A **visual baseline tag** is an annotated git tag that freezes the last known-good trunk state before a high-risk operation. Create one in any of these situations:

1. Before opening a major-version upgrade ticket under §13 Framework Upgrade Playbook.
2. Before launching a multi-PR remediation campaign (audit fixes, security patches).
3. When a regression is detected on `main` and a rescue branch is needed (the <TICKET-ID> scenario).
4. At the close of every quarterly release cycle, regardless of upcoming work.

#### 13.4.2 Naming convention

Format: `v-baseline-YYYY-MM-DD-<short-context>`

Examples:
- `v-baseline-2026-05-06-auth-green` (last green before audit, end of auth work — <TICKET-ID>)
- `v-baseline-2026-Q2-end` (quarterly snapshot)
- `v-baseline-2026-06-01-pre-react-19` (pre-major-bump snapshot)

`<short-context>` MUST be a kebab-case slug describing the state, not the upcoming work (e.g., `auth-green` not `pre-audit`).

#### 13.4.3 Tag must be annotated

Always use `git tag -a`, never `git tag <name>` (lightweight). Lightweight tags carry no message, no tagger, no timestamp metadata — auditors will reject them as untraceable.

The tag message MUST include:
- The state being captured (one-sentence summary).
- The closing ticket or context that produced this state.
- The rescue/upgrade ticket consuming this tag, if known.
- A literal `DO NOT MOVE` directive.

#### 13.4.4 Tag is immovable

Once pushed to `origin`, a baseline tag MUST NOT be deleted, force-moved, or re-pointed. If a different commit becomes the desired baseline, create a new tag with a new date in the name. The old tag remains as historical evidence.

There is no GitHub branch-protection equivalent for tags in the current setup — discipline is manual. Any reviewer who sees a `git push --force` or `git tag -d` against a `v-baseline-*` tag in a PR description must block.

#### 13.4.5 Cross-references

- §13 Framework Upgrade Playbook consumes baseline tags as the rollback target documented in Phase 1.3 ("Define rollback criteria") and Phase 3.2 ("Rollback signal").
- <TICKET-ID> (visual baseline rescue) is the canonical example of a rescue tag in use; <TICKET-ID> (rescue branch creation) and <TICKET-ID> (reopen majors under playbook) consume `v-baseline-2026-05-06-auth-green` directly.
- VRT baselines (`tests/e2e/visual.spec.ts-snapshots/*.png`) MUST be captured from a `v-baseline-*` tag, NEVER from a commit that already contains an in-flight upgrade. This is enforced by the `visual-regression.yml` workflow's default `baseline_ref` pointing to a `v-baseline-*` tag (changed from (historical commit, pre-rename) to `v-baseline-2026-05-06-auth-green` in <TICKET-ID>). When a regression on `main` requires a rescue, regenerate the baseline from the rescue branch via `workflow_dispatch` with the new default — <TICKET-ID>/386 is the canonical example. The previous formulation (allowing any "rescue branch" without a tag) was tightened in <TICKET-ID> because rescue branches are mutable while tags are immovable per §13.4.4.

### 13.5 Cascade Audit Log (added by <TICKET-ID>)

> When the §13 playbook is invoked retrospectively against commits already on `main` (the <TICKET-ID> scenario), each cluster's adjudication is recorded here for traceability. ACCEPT-NO-OP entries document why a commit was deemed safe to leave in place; ACCEPT/REVERT/SPLIT entries link to the PR or sub-ticket that implemented the consequence.

#### 13.5.1 Entry format

Each row in the §13.5.2 audit log records:

- **Cluster**: cluster code from the parent meta-coordinator's split (e.g., `C1`, `C2`).
- **Sub-ticket**: the SCRUM-XXX that produced the decision.
- **Date**: ISO date the decision was finalized at the sub-ticket's `/verify`.
- **Commit**: short SHA on `main` of the commit being adjudicated.
- **Decision**: one of `ACCEPT-NO-OP` (no baseline bump, no code change), `ACCEPT` (baseline bump via `visual-regression.yml` workflow_dispatch with linked PNG-commit SHA), `REVERT` (`git revert` + <TICKET-ID> playbook revert PR with linked PR number), `SPLIT` (cluster sub-divided into new sub-tickets, with linked SCRUM keys).
- **Rationale**: one-line citation of the verification gate(s) that produced the decision (e.g., bundle-reach analysis, VRT diff result, build/lint/test gate outcome). Must be specific enough that an auditor can re-derive the decision from the cited evidence without re-running the full audit.

A row is appended only after the corresponding sub-ticket's `/verify` PASSes. Rows are immutable once written; if a decision is later reversed (e.g., a deferred ACCEPT becomes a REVERT), append a new row referencing the old one in the Rationale rather than editing the original.

